For detection of AA with the proposed sensor, fluorimetry and absorption were used as measuring techniques. Fig. 5
                        . A shows the changes of PNF fluorescence in the presence of different concentrations of AA. The fluorescence intensity decreased linearly with the increase of AA concentration in the range of 1–575 μM. The linear calibration curve is fitted to: (F–F0)/F0 = 0.0015[AA] + 0.0645, with a correlation coefficient of R2 = 0.9942 (Fig. 5. B) and the calculated detection limit (LOD) of 250 nM. Furthermore, upon the addition of AA, the color of the PNF solution turned from purple to colorless. As can be seen from Fig. 5. C, the absorbance of the PNF solution gradually decreases with increase in the concentration of ascorbic acid. We found that there is a good linear relationship between the absorbance of the composite at 604 nm and the concentration of AA in the range of 25–425 μM. The calibration equation was (F–F0)/F0 = 0.0004[AA] - 0.0094, with a correlation coefficient of R2 = 0.9907 (Fig. 5. D) and the calculated detection limit was 10 μM (S/N = 3). The analytical properties of the presented sensor in this study was compared with other fluorescence or colorimetric reported methods have been used for AA detection (Table 1
                        ). It can be seen that the present method shows comparable or more superior performance including a wider linear range and a lower detection limit, which exhibits great promise for AA detection in clinical diagnostics.
